FOR YEARS, Syria’s Kurdish people were largely invisible: their language, flag and festivals were all suppressed. Now, in much of the country’s north and east, they rule over the Arabs who once ruled over them. A brutal murder in a sleepy German village sparks angst about a resurgent far right. And, the surprising trend of American-style debate in China. Runtime: 22 min    Listen on: Apple Podcasts | Spotify | Google | Stitcher | TuneIn